<section xml:id="sec_base_dim_exer">
  <title>Exercises</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>A = \left[ \begin{array}{ccccr} 1\amp 3\amp 1\amp 2\amp 0\\ 0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 1 \\ 2\amp 6\amp 0\amp 0\amp 1\\ 1\amp 3\amp 2\amp 4\amp 1 \\ 3\amp 9\amp 1\amp 2\amp -1\\ 3\amp 9\amp 3\amp 6\amp 1 \end{array} \right]</m>.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a basis for <m>\Col A</m>.
              What is the dimension of <m>\Col A</m>?
              What, then, is the dimension of <m>\Nul A</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a basis for <m>\Nul A</m> and verify the dimension you found in part (a).
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>A = \left[ \begin{array}{crc} 2\amp -1\amp 1\\ 1\amp 0\amp 1 \\ 1\amp -1\amp 2 \end{array} \right]</m>.
        The eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are <m>1</m> and <m>2</m>.
        Find the dimension of each eigenspace of <m>A</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>A = \left[ \begin{array}{rrrr} 1\amp 2\amp -1\amp -1 \\ -2\amp -4\amp 2\amp 2 \\ 1\amp 2\amp -1\amp -1 \end{array} \right]</m>.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a basis for <m>\Col A</m>.
              What is the rank of <m>A</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a basis for <m>\Nul A</m>.
              What is the nullity of <m>A</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Verify the Rank-Nullity Theorem for <m>A</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The row space of <m>A</m> is the span of the rows of <m>A</m>.
              Find a basis for the row space of <m>A</m> and the dimension of the row space of <m>A</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix with <m>r</m> pivots,
        where <m>r</m> is less than or equal to both <m>m, n</m>.
        Fill in the blanks.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              The null space of <m>A</m> is a subspace of <fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The column space of <m>A</m> is a subspace of <fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose <m>r=m</m>.
              Then there is a pivot in every <fillin/> and <m>\Col A =</m> <fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose <m>r=n</m>.
              Then there is a pivot in every <fillin/> and <m>\Nul A=</m><fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>A</m> has 3 pivots, then the rank of <m>A</m> is <fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>A</m> has 3 pivots,
              then the number of free variables in the system <m>A \vx = \vzero</m> is <fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The dimension of <m>\Col A</m> is equal to the number of <fillin/>, i.e.
              <m>\dim \Col A =</m><fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The dimension of <m>\Nul A</m> is equal to the number of <fillin/>, i.e.
              <m>\dim \Nul A =</m><fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dim(\Nul A) + \dim(\Col A) =</m> <fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose the columns of <m>A</m> span <m>\R^m</m>.
              Then rank <m>A</m> is <fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly independent.
              Then <m>r=</m> <fillin/> and the dimension of <m>\Nul A</m> is <fillin/>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Prove the remaining parts of the Invertible Matrix Theorem
        (<xref ref="thm_3_d_IMT">Theorem</xref>).
        Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n \times n</m> matrix.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that <m>A</m> is invertible if and only if <m>\dim(\Nul A)= 0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Prove that <m>A</m> is invertible if and only if <m>\dim(\Col A) = n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        We can convert the language of the Rank-Nullity Theorem to matrix transformation language,
        as we show in this exercise.
        Let <m>T</m> be the matrix transformation defined by the matrix <m>A</m>.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              How is the kernel of <m>T</m> related to <m>A</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              How is the range of <m>T</m> related to <m>A</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              How is the domain of <m>T</m> related to <m>A</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Explain why the Rank-Nullity Theorem says that <m>\dim(\Ker(T)) + \dim(\Range(T)) = \dim(\Domain(T))</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>W</m> be a subspace of <m>\R^4</m>.
        What are possible values for the dimension of <m>W</m>?
        Explain.
        What are the geometric descriptions of <m>W</m> in each case?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Is it possible to find two subspaces <m>W_1</m> and <m>W_2</m> in <m>\R^3</m> such that
        <m>W_1 \cap W_2=\{ \vzero \}</m> and <m>\dim W_1=\dim W_2=2</m>?
        If possible,
        give an example and justify that they satisfy the conditions.
        If not possible, explain why not.
        <hint>
          <p>
            Dimension two leads to two linearly independent vectors in each of <m>W_i</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Determine the dimensions of the column space and null space of <m>\left[ \begin{array}{ccccc} 1\amp 2\amp 4\amp 3\amp 2 \\ 1\amp 0\amp 2\amp 1\amp 4 \\ 1\amp 1\amp 3\amp 1\amp 2 \\ 1\amp 0\amp 2\amp 2\amp 5 \end{array} \right]</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If possible,
        find a <m>3\times 4</m> matrix whose column space has dimension 3 and null space has dimension 1.
        Explain how you <em>found</em> the matrix in addition to explaining why your answer works.
        If not possible,
        explain why it is not possible to find such a matrix.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              If possible,
              find a <m>5\times 5</m> matrix whose column space has the same dimension as its null space.
              Explain how you <em>found</em> the matrix in addition to explaining why your answer works.
              If not possible,
              explain why it is not possible to find such a matrix.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              If possible,
              find a matrix <m>A</m> so that <m>\Col A = \Nul A</m>.
              Explain how you <em>found</em> the matrix in addition to explaining why your answer works.
              If not possible,
              explain why it is not possible to find such a matrix.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        In this exercise we examine why the dimension of a row space of a matrix is the same as the dimension of the column space of the matrix.
        Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Explain why row operations do not change the row space of a matrix.
              Then explain why if <m>R</m> is the reduced row echelon form of <m>A</m>,
              then <m>\Row R = \Row A</m>,
              where <m>\Row M</m> is the row space of the matrix <m>M</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Explain why the rows of <m>R</m> that contain pivots form a basis for <m>\Row R</m>,
              and also of <m>\Row A</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Explain why <m>\rank(A)</m> is the number of pivots in the matrix <m>A</m>.
              Then explain why <m>\dim(\Row A) = \dim(\Col A)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Label each of the following statements as True or False.
        Provide justification for your response.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> The dimension of the column space of a <m>3\times 2</m> matrix can be three.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> There exists a
              <m>3\times 3</m> matrix whose column space has equal dimension as the null space.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If a set of vectors spans a subspace,
              then that set is a basis of this subspace.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If a linearly independent set of vectors spans a subspace,
              then that set is a basis of this subspace.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> The dimension of a space is the minimum number of vectors needed to span that space.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> The dimension of the null space of a
              <m>3\times 2</m> matrix can at most be 2.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> Any basis of <m>\R^4</m> contains 4 vectors.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> If <m>n</m> vectors span <m>\R^n</m>,
              then these vectors form a basis of <m>\R^n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> Every line in <m>\R^n</m> is a one-dimensional subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> Every plane through origin in <m>\R^n</m> is a two-dimensional subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <em>True/False</em> In <m>\R^n</m> any <m>n</m> linearly independent vectors form a basis.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
</section>